lacing a patched class in test sources violate these rules?\n../2236-667bbf3b/human-intervention-logs/com.jcraft:jsch:0.1.27/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-06T20-07-26-464063Z.log:6375:[thinking] **Exploring coverage report options**\n../2236-667bbf3b/human-intervention-logs/com.jcraft:jsch:0.1.27/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-06T20-07-26-464063Z.log:6377:[thinking] I’m contemplating how to handle dynamic coverage reports. It seems the task expects something feasible, but if the JaCoCo coverage shows \"Unknown Source,\" that complicates matters. I need to consider that if the report shows null lines, it indicates no coverage with the current artifact. User mentions iterations, so I wonder if using a debug-compiled variant of the artifact could help. Maybe loading the same class from test classes instead of the dependency could provide line numbers, but I need to follow the rules about test placement.\n../2236-667bbf3b/human-intervention-logs/com.jcraft:jsch:0.1.27/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-06T20-07-26-464063Z.log:6381:[thinking] I'm thinking about how to focus on tests while possibly creating a test fixture in an external package. Dynamic access targets the library coordinate, especially if the classpath entry for the original jar is being tracked. If a shadow class appears earlier in the classpath, the native image might still reference the original jar. However, there's the issue of runtime using the test class version, which might not track line numbers. I need to remember that the dynamic report comes from the library jar during image build, so if the test class shadows the original, it may not be used.\n../2236-667bbf3b/human-intervention-logs/com.jcraft:jsch:0.1.27/add-new-library-support/pi-generation-2026-05-06T20-07-26-464063Z.log:6391:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering dynamic coverage issues**\\n\\n