endency substitution or `flatDir`. I must ensure the group and artifact match. Creating a configuration for the source seems better, but I need to keep the test directory portable. I’m also suspicious about the source context path not likely being part of the repository in CI — that could cause issues. \\n\\nCould I perhaps use a source jar from Maven at build time to compile? Then again, I need to figure out how to keep it version-agnostic. A lot to weigh here!\\n\\n**Defining Gradle configurations**\\n\\nI can set up a configuration called `jschSources` to include the dependency \\\"com.jcraft:jsch:$libraryVersion:sources\\\" and create a task for unzipping and compiling it into a jar using `JavaCompile`. Then I’m considering whether to publish it or simply use dependency substitution for the project, which sounds simpler. \\n\\nI could create a Gradle task named `debugJschJar` that would unzip the sources and compile them into `build/jsch-debug/classes`, then package that into a jar. But I’ll have to use `testImplementation files(debugJschJar)`, since `resolveTestedLibraryJars` only tracks resolved artifacts, not file dependencies — that doesn't have a module group or name, so it won't be tracked.\\n\\n**Reviewing debugging options**\\n\\nI'm thinking about making the runtime use the debug jar earlier than the original, so I can manually track the debug jar with line numbers. However, the report still includes the original. It seems like some original calls might not be reachable. I need to explore TrackDynamicAccess, which reports dynamic call sites statically from the path, to see if all the original elements remain unaffected. I should check the dynamic access output files for more clarity.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_0270f4b9bb8643fe0169fba1b1e9ac819191bc1047aead622e\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp-6HCE66zt4IzYd1dRseNlbVm_e8oSwKyz5ou_NjOdLwBvIqjj_eDepkBPElkGVHBco1gOspZdHuLLDngkbuwga2BaBjFNb45fectdem