 build adjustments**\\n\\nI'm thinking about whether using substitution could produce some kind of artifact group or name for a local project. It feels like a lot to handle, but adding a dependency substitution seems easier, where I can use a locally compiled jar with the same coordinates that includes source with debug. \\n\\nI wonder if it's acceptable to change the build setup without altering the tests, as the user asked for test modifications. Keeping tests outside the library packages is essential, but if I compile the source as a separate jar, I might be rebuilding the library from upstream just for coverage, which could be too broad. Another thought was modifying the user-code filter, but that's not getting anywhere. I could try forcing native-image to include source info with a specific option, but that may not address the lack of line numbers in the bytecode, as those would be absent. It looks challenging to work around that.\\n\\n**Exploring build options**\\n\\nI'm considering generating a dynamic access report by building a new jar from source with debug information, which I could then use as a test dependency. The local jar needs to have the same GAV to ensure that `resolveTestedLibraryJars` can track it. \\n\\nMaybe adding a local Maven repository could work? But since `build.gradle` currently uses Maven for `testImplementation`, I’m pondering whether I can override it using dependency substitution or `flatDir`. I must ensure the group and artifact match. Creating a configuration for the source seems better, but I need to keep the test directory portable. I’m also suspicious about the source context path not likely being part of the repository in CI — that could cause issues. \\n\\nCould I perhaps use a source jar from Maven at build time to compile? Then again, I need to figure out how to keep it version-agnostic. A lot to weigh here!\\n\\n**Defining Gradle configurations**\\n\\nI can set up a configuration called `jschSources` to include the dependency \\\"com.jcraft:jsch:$libraryVersion:sources\\\" and create a task for unzipping and compiling it into a jar using `JavaCompile`. Then I’m considering whether to publish it or simply use dependency substitution for the project, which sounds simpler. \\n\\nI could create a Gradle task named `debugJschJar` that would unzip the sources and compile them into `build/jsch-debug/classes`, then package that into a jar. But I’ll have to use `testImplementation files(debugJschJar)`, since `resolveTestedLibraryJars` only tracks resolved artifacts, not file dependencies — that doesn't have a module group or name, so it won't be tracked.\\n\\n**Reviewing debugging options**\\n\\nI'm thinking about making the runtime use the debug jar earlier than the original, so I can manually track the debug jar with line numbers. However, the report still includes the original. It seems like some original calls might not be reachable. I need to explore TrackDynamicAccess, which reports dynamic call sites statically from the path, to see if all the original elements remain unaffected. I should check the dynamic access output files for more clarity.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_0270f4b9bb8643fe0169fba1b1e9ac819191bc1047aead622e\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp-6HCE66zt4IzYd1dRseNlbVm_e8oSwKyz5ou_NjOdLwBvIqjj_eDepkBPElkGVHBco1gOspZdHuLLDngkbuwga2BaBjFNb45fectdem2rTR1zm_xKPf597RqlOz_--g0YYvfN6QEgbtCTt5UermbvLKq83DDsUoUD1ICTVosIjpvJUhJ2hWMOZDQsK90Aq8xcDlOuxLr0abeByDAgNKr_CRJBLgWW2DHlcfH2Ikn-ZTTyQbwCiBqsza3zHHjMnBgd7b0KL-I75hFKJEBoUXbw0U7pw8iJioc-EOsS9h_R78RQaeNX5TENUSz-q8CFjb4bsyNGNY7KQa10pMedMUy4tMPcS-YsxibZhiTTNNgJPEgX-XaAe-B3WvhKnVkDugQnSxZD21Jm49ndT_0Ar7klAt3ADja_z6JeyPYMQXc0h2TEWPcYhHqDB3HV61SuKhfWIRj47fEv0myGU9eHeO2fkgjnfY4euQ8SehKIyrL4pSCpywXD_k-bya6ejFTij2XOpgeFQK35EGUZ6dQmReQnLGv1us2_oYsm6APNTtgTD5Y8Vrp8Z8w8o1H8IPt4SxMqf3XYm0V345VZqdC-cRPUbd86fmusAYBISKBnVN1ekX-p9Hj1YERLTEWR7OcFc_q16XXcY8-5urtPmeBniYjTRptypash84QW9D2T1oWEbYDjFv