eserve=path=` would help, or maybe using `--debug-attach`? It seems like the JaCoCo source key doesn't have lines for \\\\\\\"Unknown Source,\\\\\\\" and I'm brainstorming other potential solutions. Perhaps recompiling could help with dynamic reports, but making debug classes and patching the JAR seems risky and not allowed. I could consider adding source debug info to the original JAR at build time. It feels broad, so I might need to refine the approach further.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Investigating dynamic access reporting**\\\\n\\\\nI’m examining why the dynamic access report from the original JAR shows null lines and if it affects test classes. The `-H:TrackDynamicAccess=path=<original jar>` build arguments don’t track test classes, so that’s a dead end. However, I might try `-H:TrackDynamicAccess=path=<build/classes/java/test>` to include test versions. If I can parse library classes and configure JaCoCo's class directories properly, I could get coverage information for the test class that shadows the Session class. It seems like modifying the build.gradle file could help too.\\\"},{\\\"type\\\":\\\"summary_text\\\",\\\"text\\\":\\\"**Exploring test class coverage**\\\\n\\\\nI'm considering the dynamic report from the test class that includes line numbers, which could help mark covered lines. But then I realize this conflicts with the guideline to keep tests outside of library packages, as the source is in a library package. I wonder if instead of writing the full Session class, I could just create a subclass? However, for the dynamic call sites, I still need to ensure that the frame matches exactly with `com.jcraft.jsch.Session.*`. It’s tricky!\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_Pnc2BgkJ18rcd9gfYeoNBiP6|fc_0270f4b9bb8643fe0169fba1d855a4819198f2fec87430f0f0\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"JAR=$(find ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/com.jcraft/jsch/0.1.27 -name 'jsch-0.1.27.jar' | head 